{"questionId":"2738616","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The regions bounded by the curve and the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis are denoted by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, … , as shown on the above diagram.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the area of region <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math>.</p>\n<p>Give your answer in the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>π</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>area of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mrow><munderover><mo>∫</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></munderover><mi>cos</mi><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Modulus may be seen at a later stage.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><msubsup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mi>sin</mi><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></mrow></mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"false\"><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><